<img srcset="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Gsjgk2HvUp0ctz9VJAPVBLadLx0=/0x0:5745x3587/320x0/filters:focal(0x0:5745x3587):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23633064/GettyImages_1124819793.jpg 320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/FCcjBkVdTwexChdhe2rVDhEYvlc=/0x0:5745x3587/520x0/filters:focal(0x0:5745x3587):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23633064/GettyImages_1124819793.jpg 520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/8z6h8KWrd8fu5wXuobuuqbMWRpk=/0x0:5745x3587/720x0/filters:focal(0x0:5745x3587):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23633064/GettyImages_1124819793.jpg 720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/IOjEGskIzVV3B_Nt2Gd0V4p-h6U=/0x0:5745x3587/920x0/filters:focal(0x0:5745x3587):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23633064/GettyImages_1124819793.jpg 920w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/cQZ_D4OGxQTmjxhfLfBzAJE_X0A=/0x0:5745x3587/1120x0/filters:focal(0x0:5745x3587):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23633064/GettyImages_1124819793.jpg 1120w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/nwGSnjS7MfYjQpA15a6v0MtyaeA=/0x0:5745x3587/1320x0/filters:focal(0x0:5745x3587):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23633064/GettyImages_1124819793.jpg 1320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/nLqoB9VaPLsg1Mc_h_iWKieOHzw=/0x0:5745x3587/1520x0/filters:focal(0x0:5745x3587):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23633064/GettyImages_1124819793.jpg 1520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/MVHEdQV99IC3bgdrSnHQPFmArVI=/0x0:5745x3587/1720x0/filters:focal(0x0:5745x3587):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23633064/GettyImages_1124819793.jpg 1720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/W54WDEA4Ycms2C4OVS7S1vRYXxQ=/0x0:5745x3587/1920x0/filters:focal(0x0:5745x3587):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23633064/GettyImages_1124819793.jpg 1920w" sizes="90vw" alt="" data-upload-width="5745" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/fAE4yCYJ5bEdGf91ddwHdn63Z8E=/0x0:5745x3587/1200x0/filters:focal(0x0:5745x3587):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23633064/GettyImages_1124819793.jpg">

</source></picture>

      
    </span>
    
  </span>
  
    <span class="e-image__meta">
      
        <figcaption>Employees work at a distribution station in the 855,000-square-foot Amazon fulfillment center in Staten Island, New York, in February 2019. </figcaption>
      
      
        <cite>Johannes Eisele/AFP via Getty Images</cite>
      
    </span>
  
</figure>

</div>
<p id="7WcGzE">The internal document also suggested Amazon needs to become more efficient at hiring. At the time the report was written, Amazon needed 6.7 job applicants to apply to fill a single warehouse role. Around 9 percent of applicants were rejected either because they were former employees not permitted to be rehired or because they failed a drug test or had an unsatisfactory background check. (Later in 2021, Amazon said it would <a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2021/06/01/amazon-backs-federal-bill-to-legalize-marijuana-.html">stop screening</a> many of its warehouse worker applicants for marijuana use.)</p>
<p id="W4l0S7">Of course, Amazon could also simply reduce the number of workers it needs by speeding up automation in its warehouses — a controversial approach. Nonetheless, the report revealed that Amazon executives had already in 2021 set a “conservative” goal of improving warehouse productivity by 25 percent by the end of 2024, strictly through increased automation. Hitting that goal on its own would push back the labor crisis as well, but only slightly.</p>
<p id="No73GZ">The research team also pondered improvements that could be made to how Amazon already utilizes its existing staff. Amazon’s warehouse staff worked, on average, a little more than 27 hours a week in 2020, according to internal data. If Amazon had increased that weekly number by just 10 percent, the company could have reduced new hires by 118,000 people, the internal report estimated. The report also referenced a team in Amazon’s HR division, called Hamilton, that is building tools to automatically transfer workers between nearby facilities based on staffing levels and order volume. The relocations would come in the form of both “permanent transfers and short-term assignments.”</p>
<p id="UNvM0R">Lastly, according to the report, Amazon’s HR staffing division wants to play a bigger role in influencing where new warehouses are located so they can ensure the available labor pool is large enough for the company’s needs. For some types of Amazon warehouses, there is little wiggle room. Amazon delivery stations, for example, are the last stop for a package before it’s delivered, so they need to be located within a short driving distance to a large number of Amazon customers. But for others — like “cross dock” facilities that receive merchandise from suppliers, and fulfillment centers that receive goods from cross dock facilities and pack them into customer orders — there is more leeway in the location selection process and so an opportunity to better use internal labor forecasting tools. </p>
<p id="kqeaKG">“Our longer-term strategy … is to apply labor forecasts to future site selection,” the report read. </p>
<div class="c-wide-block">  <figure class="e-image">
  <span class="e-image__inner">
    
    <span class="e-image__image " data-original="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg">
      
        <picture class="c-picture" data-cid="site/picture_element-1665217383_6194_237920" data-cdata='{"asset_id":23632981,"ratio":"*"}'>
  


  <source srcset="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/T4PyP5Ra9PxZhILebhllFlR8Hp8=/0x0:2400x1614/320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/zf_K6DMIRigwp7ZEx4H7_FNHObE=/0x0:2400x1614/520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/fE6csaKvnfvSIDiRahJqEpmhBFM=/0x0:2400x1614/720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Opo8YcHp8OfPnztqBo_60m2_W98=/0x0:2400x1614/920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 920w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/PFWUqSstorLYSu5J83qkyNlDePU=/0x0:2400x1614/1120x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 1120w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/bTKO8DeJBaSiyEwC0-GZUICMTWY=/0x0:2400x1614/1320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 1320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Agd-us1dxKEtH_B1xc5JOpM1dT4=/0x0:2400x1614/1520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 1520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/XcQSb2NwuFDyjMyWKJTflp27rFA=/0x0:2400x1614/1720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 1720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/DByJC5nuzSb0om0L9i21vYR1Wzs=/0x0:2400x1614/1920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 1920w" sizes="90vw" type="image/webp">


<img srcset="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/cFwjnuANvLto8fy5SIM8ENcEc8M=/0x0:2400x1614/320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/2Omyg1Y84wPFTfY9BXrv4JQZSbA=/0x0:2400x1614/520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/dSkdycDE15wCs-5dKl8Pru4e3rs=/0x0:2400x1614/720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/ohWMX-11HsLQq8f6PkO7JuFhvUM=/0x0:2400x1614/920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 920w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/hGoeqpBWoOW_59SMhcS5qG6Rgu4=/0x0:2400x1614/1120x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 1120w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/p9Kgx_qNLpguLsjtuahwaQ9fOP0=/0x0:2400x1614/1320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 1320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/5k4l_ZicmCNnqR8EHl4-D10kQZI=/0x0:2400x1614/1520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 1520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/NnCk3TVUfg19g-BoloEeZHfgcNY=/0x0:2400x1614/1720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 1720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/-6tJWS6fXUmukVBy1vIvb9GBn5w=/0x0:2400x1614/1920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg 1920w" sizes="90vw" alt="" data-upload-width="2400" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/RT8YdInRlrYqHm4Vi0g_wkNVFm0=/0x0:2400x1614/1200x0/filters:focal(0x0:2400x1614):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/23632981/GettyImages_1136921906.jpg">

</source></picture>

      
    </span>
    
  </span>
  
    <span class="e-image__meta">
      
        <figcaption>Warehouse associate Patricia Sahuaqu checks labels on boxes before they are loaded on trucks to be shipped out of Amazon’s fulfillment center in Thornton, Colorado, in March 2019.</figcaption>
      
      
        <cite>Helen H. Richardson/MediaNews Group/The Denver Post via Getty Images</cite>
      
    </span>
  
</figure>

</div>
<p id="ZrZ4Lc">Overall, the leaked report offers a variety of solutions to choose from, but each with trade-offs that Amazon executives may not find palatable. Raise wages and the company may need to pull back spending elsewhere. Increase automation and risk the wrath of critics concerned about replacing people with robots at the second-largest private sector employer in the country. A focus on better retaining employees could also mean reducing performance tracking and productivity quotas that have played a role, however controversial, in the company’s historic business success to date. </p>
<p id="SirEuH">Amazon has shown time and time again that it values “customer obsession” — and the promises it makes to its customers — above all else. But the customer loyalty that results from that obsession is ultimately at risk if Amazon cannot employ enough people — or robots — to pack and ship the boxes people expect to find outside their front door a day or two after clicking “Place your order.” The company’s new <a href="https://www.aboutamazon.com/news/company-news/2021-letter-to-shareholders" has-subtag="true" data-cdata='{"rewritten_url":"https://www.aboutamazon.com/news/company-news/2021-letter-to-shareholders?ascsubtag=[]vx[p]22934941[m]m-placeholder[s]s-placeholder[t]w[c]c-placeholder[r]r-placeholder[d]d-placeholder","subtag_max_length":99,"subtag_delim_length":2,"subtag_key":"ascsubtag","subtag_data":{"ascsubtag":"[]vx[p]22934941[m]m-placeholder[s]s-placeholder[t]w[c]c-placeholder[r]r-placeholder[d]d-placeholder"},"encode_subtag":false}'>CEO, Andy Jassy, has proclaimed</a> that Amazon is “not close to being done in how we improve the lives of our employees.” As the internal report shows, doing so should no longer be optional for Amazon; it’s an imperative.</p>
  <div class="c-article-footer">
  <hr class="p-entry-hr">
  
    <p><strong><a href="https://www.vox.com/pages/support-now?utm_campaign=fall2022-apple-article-footer&utm_content=footer_link&utm_medium=referral&utm_source=apple_news">Our goal this month</a></strong></p>
  
  <p>
    Now is not the time for paywalls. Now is the time to point out what’s hidden in plain sight (for instance, the hundreds of election deniers on ballots across the country), clearly explain the answers to voters’ questions, and give people the tools they need to be active participants in America’s democracy.  Reader gifts help keep our well-sourced, research-driven explanatory journalism free for everyone. By the end of September, we’re aiming to add 5,000 new financial contributors to our community of Vox supporters. <a href="https://www.vox.com/pages/support-now?utm_campaign=fall2022-apple-article-footer&utm_content=footer_link&utm_medium=referral&utm_source=apple_news "> Will you help us reach our goal by making a gift today?
